  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "p+VebUpqi5/RiAvWb6T2Td72L1M=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:39.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "# operation errors are recorded on operations not thrown to callers\n\nPowerhouse handles reducer errors differently from typical throw/catch patterns. When a reducer throws an error:\n\n1. The operation is **still recorded** in `document.operations.global` (or `.local`)\n2. The error message is stored in `operation.error` as a string\n3. The **state is NOT mutated** \u2014 it remains as it was before the operation\n\nThis means error testing looks different:\n\n```typescript\n// \u2705 Correct \u2014 check the operation's error property\nconst updated = reducer(document, setName({ name: \"invalid\" }));\nexpect(updated.operations.global[0].error).toBe(\"Name is not allowed\");\nexpect(updated.state.global.name).toBe(initialState);\n\n// \u274c Wrong \u2014 errors are not propagated to the caller\nexpect(() => reducer(document, setName({ name: \"invalid\" }))).toThrow();\n```\n\nSince [[operation error index must match the number of prior dispatches]], the index into `operations.global` depends on how many operations were dispatched before this one.\n\n---\n\nTopics:\n- [[reducer patterns]]",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:39.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:39.000Z"
    }
  },
